  "configuration_source": "configs/experiment/convergence.json",
  "id": "EXP-02",
  "interpretation": "Both schemes attain their theoretical strong orders. Measured on common Brownian paths -- the discretised and exact paths share every shock, differing only in the stepping rule -- Euler-Maruyama converges at order 1/2 and Milstein at order 1, with each asymptotic 95% interval covering the theoretical value. The practical consequence is the error ratio: Milstein's advantage grows without bound as the grid refines, so on fine grids it is not a marginal improvement but a different class of accuracy for the same number of shocks. Fitted over the full grid the slopes fall short of theory, because the error is C*dt^k only to leading order and the coarse levels still carry the neglected terms. That the local orders climb monotonically toward theory as the grid refines is what distinguishes this from a wrong order, and it is why the verdict rests on an asymptotic window fixed before the run.",
  "limitations": [
    "baseline / euler_maruyama: the full-range slope 0.4974 [0.4955, 0.4994] excludes the theoretical 0.5, while the asymptotic window gives 0.4996 [0.4936, 0.5055], which covers it. The coarse levels are pre-asymptotic; the local orders climb from 0.495 to 0.504 as the grid refines.",
    "baseline / milstein: the full-range slope 0.9838 [0.9740, 0.9937] excludes the theoretical 1, while the asymptotic window gives 0.9957 [0.9845, 1.0068], which covers it. The coarse levels are pre-asymptotic; the local orders climb from 0.945 to 1.001 as the grid refines.",
    "high_volatility / milstein: the full-range slope 0.9641 [0.9456, 0.9826] excludes the theoretical 1, while the asymptotic window gives 0.9884 [0.9713, 1.0056], which covers it. The coarse levels are pre-asymptotic; the local orders climb from 0.900 to 1.001 as the grid refines.",
    "long_maturity / euler_maruyama: the full-range slope 0.4969 [0.4945, 0.4993] excludes the theoretical 0.5, while the asymptotic window gives 0.4997 [0.4925, 0.5069], which covers it. The coarse levels are pre-asymptotic; the local orders climb from 0.493 to 0.505 as the grid refines.",
    "long_maturity / milstein: the full-range slope 0.9843 [0.9739, 0.9947] excludes the theoretical 1, while the asymptotic window gives 0.9956 [0.9826, 1.0087], which covers it. The coarse levels are pre-asymptotic; the local orders climb from 0.942 to 1.004 as the grid refines.",
    "Only the terminal value is compared. A pathwise supremum error would be the stronger statement and is not measured here; it is what a barrier payoff would be sensitive to (EXP-09).",
    "Levels are not coupled to one another: each grid draws its own Brownian path, so the error estimates across levels are independent rather than nested. This costs precision in the fit, not correctness -- each level's error is a valid expectation on its own grid.",
    "GBM only. Both orders are theoretical results under global Lipschitz coefficients, which GBM satisfies and Heston's square-root diffusion does not; nothing here transfers to EXP-04's Heston arm."
  ],
  "name": "Strong SDE Convergence",
  "question": "Do Euler-Maruyama and Milstein achieve their expected strong convergence orders?",
  "reproduction_command": "diffusionworks experiment --id EXP-02",
